Part 4

Reddy was waiting outside the Secretariat gate when Vikram's car pulled up, standing in the shade of a neem tree with the particular stillness of a man who has waited outside enough government offices to have stopped minding it.

"You look well-rested," Reddy said, by way of greeting, sounding almost suspicious of the fact.

"Ramanna's wedding. His daughter's."

"Whose wedding?"

"Long story."

Reddy studied him a moment, decided not to pursue it, and turned toward the entrance instead. "Don't expect the same hospitality in here."

---

The Minister's outer office ran on its own private clock — twenty minutes became forty, forty became an hour, while a peon brought two rounds of tea nobody had asked for and a queue of other petitioners came and went ahead of them with the ease of people who'd learned exactly which palms needed greasing and which didn't.

"This is normal," Reddy said, not looking up from his files. "Don't take it personally."

"I'm not."

"You're checking your watch every four minutes."

Vikram stopped checking his watch.

---

Minister Satyanarayana, when they were finally shown in, turned out to be a small, unhurried man behind a very large desk, who gestured them to sit without getting up himself, and came to the point faster than the wait outside had suggested he would.

"Liquor," the Minister said, as if tasting the word and not much liking it. "You know what that word does to my file in this state?"

"I understand it's sensitive—"

"Sensitive." The Minister smiled without warmth. "My predecessor lost his seat over a liquor policy. Not because people stopped drinking. Because the opposition made him the man who let the poor man's family go hungry so he could drink. Doesn't matter if it's true. It only has to be sayable."

Reddy leaned forward. "Sir, with respect, the industry exists whether or not this company enters it. We're asking for land allocation for a compliant, licensed unit. Nothing about the moral question changes because of who holds the license."

"Everything about the moral question changes based on whose name is on the license, Reddy garu. You know this game as well as I do." The Minister looked at Vikram directly for the first time. "Your father's company. Big name. Big target, if anyone wants to make an example."

"So the land isn't available," Vikram said.

"I didn't say that." The Minister leaned back. "I said it isn't available easily. There's a difference, and the difference costs time, not just money."

---

Outside, back in the car, Reddy didn't bother softening it.

"This is what I meant, in the boardroom. This isn't home ground. Here, every 'no' has to be understood as maybe, and every 'maybe' has to be earned twice over, because nobody owes your name anything yet."

"I heard you the first time. In the boardroom."

"Hearing and understanding aren't the same thing," Reddy said, not unkindly. "I'll be honest, Vikram. I still don't know if this land comes through in a month or in three years. Could go either way. Could not go at all."

Vikram looked out the window at the Secretariat gate shrinking behind them.

"Then we wait," he said, "and we don't waste the waiting."

Reddy glanced at him sideways, as if that sentence hadn't sounded quite like the Vikram he'd expected on this trip, and said nothing about it, filing the observation away the way careful men file things they intend to bring up again later.
